<font color="#FF0000">PERCEPTIONS</font><br>
<tt>Thu Oct  9 20:21:58 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Lin,<br><br>
The history I speak about goes back much farther than the short history of the US.  We are on a cycle of rise and fall if history is allowed to repeat.  The history such as the Roman Empire and others.  Method does not change much.<br><br>
It is without a doubt that most wars were not to defend our basic freedoms.  Politics and money, pure economics normally.  I find that WWII was no exception.  Japan did not want to conquer our land.  They only wanted to keep us out of their Pacific realm.  We forced their hand with Scrap metal and oil reserves.   Economics again.<br><br>
Most men I know do think the protestors were anti-American and anti- soldier.  The media made things appear that way and actions to include Jane Fonda did reinforce the belief.<br><br>
I for one am not naive enough to believe the war had the best or most noble intentions or that the politics did not stink.  We left POWs behind and even in Korea.  The soldier knows that.  Know anybody, but us that cares now.?<br><br>
The problem is that we believed in our country, our oath, and our duty to serve.  Archaic maybe, but the beliefs of the old guard.  As we look at the new soldiers it is not likely this type of discussion would ever materialize.<br><br>
Values have changed.  Not for the better I think, but one we will have to live with.<br><br>
I served proudly as did my fathers and their fathers before them.  A history of proud soldiers for hundreds of years.<br><br>
I totally agree we have supported some of the worst leaders in history and continue to do so.  Even now the nation grows weaker, with less resolve and less capability.  I am a student of history and the trend bothers me.<br><br>
The tone of our dialogue does give me some hope that we may at least agree we must be united in our goal of maintaining the best nation on earth and not focus on those issues of disagreement.<br>

<p><code>--   (SW) </code><p>


